It would be useful to enable this wiki feature within JIRA Issues.

This would help when adding *big chunks of code* (with the useful formatting) within an issue.

\{code:title=Test Title|borderStyle=solid|collapse=true}
// Comment
public class Hello1
\{
 public static void Main()
 \{
 System.Console.WriteLine("Hello, World!");
 }
}
\{code}

Having to link an attached text file instead is not useful.

h3. Problem Definition
# Hyperlinks are automatically rendered on JIRA issues. 
# Some users would like the hyperlink renderer to be disabled for security for example:
bq. The URL(s) for alerts generated from the SIEM tools are not sanitized and accidental clicking on these links might impact the Laptops of professionals.

h3. Suggested Solution
Introduce a feature to disable hyperlinks rendered on JIRA
 
h3. Workaround
One quick way is to manually encode the first character of your URL so that the rendering engine does not recognize it as a URL. For example the letter h is encoded as:
{noformat}
&#104;
{noformat}

Thus a link should be entered as 
{code}
&#104;ttps://www.google.com
{code}

which will output as &#104;ttps://www.google.com

h3. Summary
At the moment, when creating an issue via REST API, the response when successful is very little
{code}{
  "id": "11000",
  "key": "SPA-29",
  "self": "http://localhost:7330/jira733/rest/api/2/issue/11000"
}{code}

Previously in SOAP API, much more information was returned

h3. Suggestion
Return the entire issue detail (similar to running a GET /api/2/issue/\{issueKeyOrId\}) when creating an issue via REST API

Currently a space is not considered a special character when you set a custom password policy that requires at least two combinations for character variety. For example, a password like this should be acceptable, but isn't: 
{noformat}
the limit does not exist{noformat}
 

When you attempt to set the password above you get the following message:
 * The password must contain at least 2 different kinds of characters, such as uppercase letters, lowercase letters, numeric digits, and punctuation marks.

JIRA has block format styles for code and for preformatted text. Unlike many other issue trackers, it does not offer a dedicated inline style for code (like Markdown's `code`). But it has a 'preformatted' inline style that can be (ab-)used for short, inline code fragments, to at least get a monospaced font style.

One huge problem with this approach is that the preformatted inline style still applies nested markup and - more annoyingly - emoji replacement, {{as can be seen in _this example_ (:imaginary code snippet:)}}

I would suggest to either introduce a new inline style akin to {{{{noformat}}}}, or better yet, make the inline preformatted style work that way by default (of course the dream would be to have a dedicated inline `code` style).
